<exercise checkit-seed="0008" checkit-slug="L4" checkit-title="Argument Analysis with Tables">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Consider the following argument.
            <ul>
                <li>Premise 1: if everybody is laid back, then I have a healthy diet.</li>
                <li>Premise 2: it is false that if I have a healthy diet, then it is false that a hot dog is a sandwich.</li>
                <li>Conclusion: if everybody is laid back, then it is false that a hot dog is a sandwich.</li>
            </ul>
            First translate this multi-line argument into the long implication that describes it in pure logic. Clearly state how you are assigning the variables P, Q, and possibly R. Then determine if the argument is valid using a truth table. Make sure your table is in the standard order.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p> First off, in symbols the argument is
            <ul>
                <li>Premise 1: <m>P \rightarrow Q</m></li>
                <li>Premise 1: <m> \sim Q \rightarrow  \sim R</m></li>
                <li>Conclusion: <m>P \rightarrow  \sim R</m></li>
            </ul>
        This means that the long implication that describes the argument is <m>((P \rightarrow Q) \wedge ( \sim Q \rightarrow  \sim R)) \rightarrow (P \rightarrow  \sim R)</m>. The truth table for that is below.</p>
        <m>
        \begin{array}{lllcc} P &amp; Q &amp; R &amp; \cdots &amp; ((P \rightarrow Q) \wedge ( \sim Q \rightarrow  \sim R)) \rightarrow (P \rightarrow  \sim R) \\ \hline \text{True} &amp; \text{True} &amp; \text{True} &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{False} \\ \text{True} &amp; \text{True} &amp; \text{False} &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{True} &amp; \text{False} &amp; \text{True} &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{True} &amp; \text{False} &amp; \text{False} &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{True} &amp; \text{True} &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{True} &amp; \text{False} &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{False} &amp; \text{True} &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{False} &amp; \text{False} &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \end{array}
        </m>
        <p>The argument is not valid by because there is at least one false entry in the final column of the truth table.</p>
    </answer>
</exercise>
